00:28:57,923 --> 00:29:07,408
Would each of these different locations have a component, an AV component to be able to include people that aren't able to be there in person as well?

220
00:29:10,262 --> 00:29:18,516
I guess in my head I always imagined award meeting as being an in-person thing, but now that you said it that way, it probably should have a Zoom component to it.

221
00:29:24,159 --> 00:29:36,908
So if it's logistically possible, then sure, it should be hybrid, but that is a little bit difficult to set up.

222
00:29:37,829 --> 00:29:42,312
I mean, a ward meeting could be something that takes place in...

223
00:29:43,172 --> 00:29:44,493
City Hall, like a formal meeting.

224
00:29:44,913 --> 00:29:50,695
It could also be sitting at a restaurant with a couple of neighbors at a table.

225
00:29:50,795 --> 00:29:59,018
So the format for these things could be something we might have to experiment with and figure out what works well and what doesn't.

226
00:29:59,038 --> 00:30:02,579
Thank you.

227
00:30:02,679 --> 00:30:04,720
Councillor Callahan.

228
00:30:06,721 --> 00:30:06,921
Thanks.

229
00:30:07,241 --> 00:30:10,322
Yeah, I'm going to say that it might be good

230
00:30:11,605 --> 00:30:14,247
I might suggest we do them separately.

231
00:30:14,827 --> 00:30:17,710
Like hybrid meetings are very difficult to make work.

232
00:30:17,870 --> 00:30:18,690
Very, very difficult.

233
00:30:18,970 --> 00:30:22,333
But we could have an in-person and a hybrid for each ward.

234
00:30:22,353 --> 00:30:26,376
Or sorry, in-person and a Zoom virtual for each ward.

235
00:30:26,436 --> 00:30:30,019
And that gives people the opportunity to come in person if they're more of an in-person person.

236
00:30:31,299 --> 00:30:35,721
If they'd rather do it on Zoom or they're not available or whatever, then they can do the Zoom meeting.

237
00:30:35,741 --> 00:30:38,643
I don't think they have to be just one.

238
00:30:38,663 --> 00:30:43,605
I mean, some people won't be able to make it whatever time we choose anyway.

239
00:30:43,645 --> 00:30:44,906
So having a couple might be nice.

240
00:30:46,186 --> 00:30:53,450
One of the things I'm wondering... By the way, if it is in person, I think it's a great idea to see if we can get even the tiniest budget for like...

241
00:30:54,190 --> 00:30:58,051
you know, some snacks, something to make it, you know, fun and social.

242
00:30:59,551 --> 00:31:19,115
And I'm also thinking that while I want to try to ensure that we reach people in the wards that have, that tend to have low voter turnout, like wards seven and one and the ones that tend not to be as engaged, I want to make sure that we

243
00:31:20,233 --> 00:31:24,315
do those but if we do them first and those are kind of the ones we're experimenting on.

244
00:31:24,755 --> 00:31:35,461
So maybe it's better if we don't do them first but we do them after we've had a couple of successful ones in words where there are more people just trying to think of like, in terms of which ones we do for second and third.

245
00:31:38,123 --> 00:31:45,127
I mean, of course, anything, maybe we should just roll dice, because any way we decide, people are gonna feel like, oh, you chose them first.

246
00:31:45,708 --> 00:31:49,170
And maybe some sort of random way of selecting would actually be better.

247
00:31:49,190 --> 00:31:53,693
And then I do think we should have at least one in-person.

248
00:31:54,233 --> 00:31:59,716
So we should, for each ward, we should figure out a place, and if that's a restaurant or a coffee shop.

249
00:32:01,297 --> 00:32:02,037
That would be great.

250
00:32:02,077 --> 00:32:10,701
I think, you know, there's the West Memphis Community Center, there are churches, there are places, I think, that, you know, could be open to this kind of event.

251
00:32:11,441 --> 00:32:18,864
And that's something we could decide beforehand, I think, making sure that it's somewhere that everyone feels welcome and has access to.

252
00:32:19,124 --> 00:32:19,264
So.

253
00:32:20,925 --> 00:32:21,105
Great.

254
00:32:21,145 --> 00:32:21,505
Thank you.

255
00:32:25,527 --> 00:32:26,047
Councilor Sang.

256
00:32:28,446 --> 00:32:30,149
It's been helpful hearing from everyone.

257
00:32:30,169 --> 00:32:35,055
I think it helps frame the thoughts and the discussion.

258
00:32:39,562 --> 00:32:50,972
I think it does make sense in terms of ordering to also just, as Councilor Lemming alluded to, look at the zoning timeline as well.

259
00:32:51,973 --> 00:32:56,076
I know we have Wellington on there as a separate thing.

260
00:32:56,477 --> 00:33:06,225
And so it makes, it will probably make sense to do like Ward 7 a little bit, not during it, but right before that, for example,

261
00:33:08,017 --> 00:33:11,079
So maybe that can guide our thoughts a little bit too.

262
00:33:11,439 --> 00:33:35,213
With regards to like wards one and seven where we see lower voter turnout, I think that it does make a lot of sense to try to gin that up a little bit by treating those places like a priority for us to get into because very often we're kind of

263
00:33:36,070 --> 00:33:36,110
Um.

264
00:33:36,130 --> 00:33:44,394
Hearing a little bit less from those neighborhoods and the goal of these is to make sure that everyone is getting an equal voice in government as well.

265
00:33:45,114 --> 00:33:45,274
Um.

266
00:33:45,955 --> 00:33:47,696
But, um, I would.

267
00:33:48,016 --> 00:33:52,798
I would lean towards saying that maybe we do it like third or fourth, for example.

268
00:33:52,818 --> 00:33:55,920
I rather the first because I think we want to.

269
00:33:56,800 --> 00:34:00,742
I think import the best lessons that we've learned so far, and then I'm sure

270
00:34:05,833 --> 00:34:07,455
I'm not opposed to hybrid meetings.

271
00:34:07,755 --> 00:34:22,630
I just, given, you know, for example, what happened to the Roberts, just how difficult technically it was running that meeting last year, I wonder if it would make sense to just have

272
00:34:24,463 --> 00:34:30,428
To check if the locations that we're going to do these meetings are actually well suited for hybrid.

273
00:34:30,849 --> 00:34:37,294
And if not, maybe it would make actually more sense to do an in person and in and on a zoom version of it.

274
00:34:38,495 --> 00:34:42,779
I don't really see the harm in having more meetings and.

275
00:34:43,940 --> 00:34:48,043
They are distinct skills as well to run those two different types of meetings.

276
00:34:48,063 --> 00:34:50,205
They, you know, require us to do different things.

277
00:34:51,405 --> 00:34:57,890
And so I think that makes a lot, that would make a lot of sense to just explore the list of venues.

278
00:34:59,511 --> 00:35:10,359
Councilor Loeb, I'm not completely sure if you have the list ready or if there were specific places you had in mind, more feedback for us to get, but

279
00:35:12,540 --> 00:35:14,781
but I think we should look at that list too.

280
00:35:15,942 --> 00:35:28,269
With regards to just like a lot of the lower turnout wards, a lot of them have big apartment blocks in them and I think it would make sense for us to try to set up a meeting in an apartment block too.

281
00:35:29,849 --> 00:35:33,591
You know the river's edges, the Medford Housing Authority buildings,

282
00:35:35,578 --> 00:35:51,149
to try to work with people, the apartment associations or anyone running the building, because I think those folks are people who often do get neglected and feel left behind in city government.

283
00:35:52,150 --> 00:35:56,693
And so it'd be, I think, helpful for us to get some face time with them as well.

284
00:35:58,254 --> 00:36:01,917
Those are just some preliminary thoughts that I have right now.

285
00:36:06,479 --> 00:36:06,860
Thank you.

286
00:36:06,880 --> 00:36:07,080
Great.

287
00:36:07,140 --> 00:36:07,441
Thank you.

288
00:36:15,796 --> 00:36:24,801
In terms of the order that the wards should go in, I have a list of pairs that I think should list the general order.

289
00:36:24,821 --> 00:36:39,850
So I think that wards eight and four should probably be first on the list, mainly because we have rezoning for Medford Square and then shortly after the Tufts Institutional zoning and Boston Avenue coming up, so those should be

290
00:36:40,690 --> 00:36:44,171
very early candidates on the list.

291
00:36:45,111 --> 00:37:02,817
And after that, it's a little bit more flexible, maybe five or six after that, and then one in seven, once we have sort of, by the time we get to one in seven, we have a lot of practice doing those, and then two and three last.

292
00:37:05,532 --> 00:37:19,351
So that's my, I think those are the general chunks that we could do them in, but the only thing that I'm married to in that is just the idea that eight and four should probably be the first two that we do.

293
00:37:24,780 --> 00:37:24,980
Great.

294
00:37:25,180 --> 00:37:26,982
Thank you, Councilor Lemming.

295
00:37:27,983 --> 00:37:36,389
That does make sense to be able to line it up, especially with bigger things that we're going to be discussing with the City Council that correlate with each of these different wards.

296
00:37:37,971 --> 00:37:42,434
So just so that I'm hearing this correctly, we're going to do in-person.

297
00:37:43,775 --> 00:37:47,276
a Zoom one separate, at least at the start, to see how that goes.

298
00:37:47,356 --> 00:38:05,242
So I'm assuming if we start with awards eight and four, or however we do that, we'll still do the in-person and the hybrid within that same month, so we can make sure that it's not as confusing if we're separating meetings like this for when people are able to join us.

299
00:38:05,962 --> 00:38:08,103
Does that sound reasonable?

300
00:38:08,723 --> 00:38:20,626
And that we can start generating a list of where we see the ability to host in each one of these different wards to be able to get people to come join us in person.

301
00:38:20,646 --> 00:38:32,130
And each of the counselors will be in charge of kind of handling or running it, or is that within the committee members themselves to be able to do?

302
00:38:33,090 --> 00:38:34,931
We welcome any suggestions on that as well.

303
00:38:35,652 --> 00:38:36,199
Councilor Lohmmann.

304
00:38:39,128 --> 00:39:06,558
I would personally like the two-for-two model, so we have a pair of counselors that's in charge of the ward meetings for eight and four, just because I want to, if I'm gonna run a ward meeting, then I wanna make sure it's more than just me at that meeting, so I just spread the responsibility out a little bit, have a buddy to bounce ideas off of and just help you run the meeting.

305
00:39:07,838 --> 00:39:09,580
the listening sessions that we've done.

306
00:39:09,860 --> 00:39:18,446
The ones that I've liked the most have been the ones where I have somebody there with me also helping to field questions or facilitate.

307
00:39:18,466 --> 00:39:21,608
It's my personal preference.

308
00:39:24,250 --> 00:39:24,691
I also...

309
00:39:27,273 --> 00:39:54,913
I am a little hesitant about the idea of committing at this point to doing one in-person, one Zoom meeting for each ward, just because that, I mean, I know it sounds simple saying it here, but saying that we're going to plan 16 meetings for over the next two years is quite a lot, and that's in addition to everything else that we already do.

310
00:39:58,058 --> 00:40:08,073
Yeah, hopefully when in 2027 when there are 11 counselors that will be a little bit more work spread out to do the ward meetings.

311
00:40:12,383 --> 00:40:13,464
Thank you, Councilwoman.

312
00:40:16,166 --> 00:40:16,887
No, I agree with you.

313
00:40:16,967 --> 00:40:24,172
I think that would be quite a bit of meetings considering all of the other meetings as well that are on the calendar and I don't want it to be confusing.

314
00:40:25,713 --> 00:40:33,199
So we can kind of and I do agree having at least two or having just two counselors at each of those different meetings.

315
00:40:34,160 --> 00:40:49,201
You have someone to bounce stuff off of and to be able to help answer any kind of questions or I think it's a great way to kind of spread that out so we can start looking at how to disseminate that between each of the different wards and what that looks like.

316
00:40:50,823 --> 00:40:53,885
I did want to get back to your other point, though, about agenda items.

317
00:40:54,385 --> 00:41:11,415
It does make sense to maybe have some initial standing agenda items that we'd want to make consistent through each of the wards, but then also offering it up for each of the wards to have time to be able to either send something in that's specific or be able to bring something up obviously when we're in the meeting themselves.

318
00:41:13,597 --> 00:41:23,208
Does that sound like something that makes the most sense to be able to kind of at least keep some of it consistent but also allow for any kind of flexibility that may be a little bit more ward specific?

319
00:41:28,625 --> 00:41:44,890
I do like the idea of fielding feedback with a few weeks before the meetings from residents so that their concerns can help dictate the agenda instead of it sort of coming top down.

320
00:41:44,930 --> 00:41:47,871
I think that's an effective way of doing things.

321
00:41:47,951 --> 00:41:55,253
It's just we will have to advertise as widely as possible that these are happening.

322
00:42:00,944 --> 00:42:03,967
Thank you.

323
00:42:04,547 --> 00:42:18,842
I also want to emphasize that, you know, in some of the listening sessions that I've done, it can happen that, you know, a couple of people who already are the ones who come to City Council all the time, and we have heard from them many times,

324
00:42:19,903 --> 00:42:22,185
They can dominate the entire meeting.

325
00:42:22,585 --> 00:42:26,869
So I think what's really important in these meetings is facilitating.

326
00:42:26,949 --> 00:42:35,196
I once did a meeting where almost the entire meeting was dominated by two people who come to City Council all the time, and when that meeting was over, I got a ride.

327
00:42:35,276 --> 00:42:40,661
Someone asked if, you know, they were like, please, can I give you a ride?

328
00:42:40,821 --> 00:42:41,681
Oh, I gave someone a ride.

329
00:42:41,701 --> 00:42:42,122
That's what it was.

330
00:42:42,542 --> 00:42:47,306
I gave someone a ride in my car and they said, that meeting was so hostile.

331
00:42:47,366 --> 00:42:49,567
I didn't feel like I could even open my mouth.

332
00:42:51,189 --> 00:42:53,771
And then they started talking to me about the things they wanted to talk about.

333
00:42:54,211 --> 00:43:01,256
So I think it's really important that when we facilitate these, we make sure that we hear from everyone, right?

334
00:43:01,296 --> 00:43:09,683
That people who are maybe not talking at least have an opportunity and that we, like what I find can be really helpful is,

335
00:43:11,624 --> 00:43:18,308
at the beginning to say, hey, we're here to talk about housing, to talk about zoning, to talk about school funding.

336
00:43:18,408 --> 00:43:22,231
We come up with a list that is fairly comprehensive for people.

337
00:43:26,553 --> 00:43:33,901
the conversation is being dominated by a few people, at some point you've got to say, hey, great, I really appreciate you bringing these issues to us.

338
00:43:34,262 --> 00:43:39,387
We just want to make sure that everyone here has an opportunity to ask questions and to speak their minds.

339
00:43:42,690 --> 00:43:45,112
let's go ahead and have a step up, step back policy, right?

340
00:43:45,152 --> 00:43:53,236
I don't know if you guys have heard of that, but that's something that sometimes people do is they just at the very beginning, they say, hey, we're going to, you know, it's our goal to hear from everyone here.

341
00:43:53,256 --> 00:44:02,182
We're going to have a step up, step back policy so that if you've been stepping up and asking some questions, then, you know, we may ask for some of those folks who have not.

342
00:44:02,462 --> 00:44:09,846
We're going to may ask them to step up and for you to step back just to kind of be, there should be some active facilitation, I think, in these conversations.

343
00:44:18,033 --> 00:44:34,558
I 100% agree with my colleague that at the listening sessions that we've been to, some of them, yes, have been dominated by people that we already have heard their concerns many times at City Council meetings.

344
00:44:34,598 --> 00:44:36,599
That is definitely a dynamic that can occur.

345
00:44:40,235 --> 00:44:58,920
echo what she said after the meetings people have come up to me and ask their actual questions and people who I know and I also know that people who like I casually know in a social context who might have happened to come to those meetings who've never been to City Council meeting before were shocked.

346
00:44:59,809 --> 00:45:04,711
at that, that was what we had to, that was the nature of these meetings.

347
00:45:05,792 --> 00:45:16,956
I will say that my natural personality is much less charming than Councilor Callahan, so I have trouble facilitating these meetings sometimes without taking residents off.

348
00:45:18,997 --> 00:45:35,609
One of my strategies for doing, for handling that is just changing the format of the meetings, and this is something that I'm giving, you know, that I've thought about and have some half-baked solutions to, which I will share at this meeting being recorded on YouTube.

349
00:45:37,430 --> 00:45:47,798
One of them is that if it's, if it is an audience meeting, like a chair audience panel, which has been the format of some of the listening sessions before,

350
00:45:48,855 --> 00:45:57,862
then it sort of sets itself up to be adversarial, especially for people who are used to the adversarial nature that city council meetings can sometimes take.

351
00:46:00,611 --> 00:46:22,941
having it be at like a large restaurant or the Great American Beer Hall or something like that where residents know that they are perfectly free to talk could be an alternate, could be an alternative to having this sort of panel style board meeting that we typically do.

352
00:46:25,643 --> 00:46:45,515
So I'm sort of leaning towards having a, like trying to host the board meeting at just a table on a Sunday in the Great American Beer Hall, and if somebody comes there super angry or wanting to dominate a conversation, they're just not able to do that quite as much at like a very social setting like that.

353
00:46:45,575 --> 00:46:51,359
So that is, that's one thing I'm thinking about, and there are other,

354
00:46:52,280 --> 00:47:00,379
So I think there are multiple ways to sort of address this issue, but it very much will be a dynamic moving forward with some of these sessions.

355
00:47:02,786 --> 00:47:03,026
Thank you.

356
00:47:03,086 --> 00:47:04,046
And I agree with you.

357
00:47:04,146 --> 00:47:11,869
I definitely want it to be a place where people feel open and able to discuss any different type of issue.

358
00:47:11,909 --> 00:47:19,232
And, you know, when I mentioned just having standing agenda items, I don't mean to ever stop people from adding other ideas to it.

359
00:47:19,272 --> 00:47:31,356
I just thought that maybe it would give a little bit more structure to what people would be expecting, that these are some of the topics, and that we always are open to hearing any other kind of thoughts.

360
00:47:31,936 --> 00:47:43,559
So, you know, I appreciate that, and I appreciate kind of the setup and how we can approach it to make people feel as comfortable as possible to be able to come and speak with us as well.

361
00:47:44,539 --> 00:47:45,179
Council Callahan.

362
00:47:47,980 --> 00:47:48,200
Thanks.

363
00:47:48,640 --> 00:47:56,902
The other thing that I have brought up before, and I understand there's some mix of opinions on this, but I think it's important.

364
00:48:00,502 --> 00:48:04,768
To me, the idea of a listening session is that we are listening to the people who arrive.

365
00:48:05,689 --> 00:48:06,811
We are listening to the residents.

366
00:48:07,271 --> 00:48:14,901
And I think, unfortunately, in these more contentious ones, the way that it ends up being is

367
00:48:16,067 --> 00:48:18,910
a resident will, like, demand answers from us.

368
00:48:19,731 --> 00:48:21,612
So they ask the questions and we answer.

369
00:48:22,413 --> 00:48:24,235
And it's just all about what our opinions are.

370
00:48:24,375 --> 00:48:26,377
And then it's they like it or they don't like it.

371
00:48:26,437 --> 00:48:32,103
So to me, what a listening session is, is we're asking questions.

372
00:48:33,744 --> 00:48:36,405
How many people live on a road that's not paved well?

373
00:48:36,505 --> 00:48:41,207
Who here has had trees that have been a stump for a long period of time?

374
00:48:42,107 --> 00:48:44,208
What is your experience of your kids in the schools?

375
00:48:44,368 --> 00:48:46,108
Do they need to take a bus?

376
00:48:47,869 --> 00:48:50,450
Us asking and finding out, how many people here are renters?

377
00:48:51,130 --> 00:48:57,715
You know, has your rent gone up like crazy like, you know, finding out from them what their lives are like and what they struggle with.

378
00:48:58,216 --> 00:49:03,740
Oh, I see there's a lot of senior citizens here like how many of you, you know, are having trouble getting around the city.

379
00:49:03,760 --> 00:49:07,043
Do you miss the transportation option that we had during coven.

380
00:49:08,364 --> 00:49:14,508
with the van that was going around, like us asking them questions, and I think there could be a balance of the two.

381
00:49:15,809 --> 00:49:26,496
So, you know, you can even be like, the first half of this will be us asking you questions, and then the second half, so please hold your questions, because the second half, we would love to hear your questions for us.

382
00:49:26,797 --> 00:49:33,621
So, I think that can help people feel like, oh, their questions will be answered,

383
00:49:34,662 --> 00:49:42,667
You know, we're not avoiding their questions, but we simply want to make sure that we also are able to, like, find out from residents, like, hey, how is this affecting you?

384
00:49:43,087 --> 00:49:47,930
Have you seen any changes because of the three, like, road and control ordinances that we passed?

385
00:49:50,711 --> 00:49:51,532
Those sorts of things.

386
00:49:54,300 --> 00:49:54,560
Thank you.

387
00:49:54,580 --> 00:50:08,324
I think those are great points, Councilor Callahan, too, because I do want to make sure that people, that they're not being talked at, that we're feeling more of a conversation and that people feel more comfortable sharing their feelings on it.

388
00:50:10,344 --> 00:50:11,244
Councilor Lemming.

389
00:50:15,866 --> 00:50:20,967
Sorry, my microphone was accidentally already on from the previous time, but Councilor Scarpelli has his.

390
00:50:24,721 --> 00:50:26,683
Councillor Scarpelli.

391
00:50:26,723 --> 00:50:27,063
Thank you.

392
00:50:27,643 --> 00:50:37,171
I appreciate everybody sharing their input with this and I like the fact that we're looking at going into the neighborhoods because I think that

393
00:50:38,699 --> 00:51:02,748
We saw when Council Falco at the time moved the community policing meetings to the neighborhoods, we really had a better turnout and really got to listen to people, but I don't want to be the, you know, like I said, I'm really trying to be positive, but as the meeting's going on, I'm getting texts from people that are watching on, that are just questioned.

394
00:51:04,308 --> 00:51:20,337
If it's a true listening session, I can understand going into that neighborhood and give some options of what they want to talk about, but then letting our residents talk, I think that's what is a little confusing of having the listening session.

395
00:51:20,377 --> 00:51:31,542
I also understand that we don't want people to dominate meetings and that's up to the council that's running that meeting to really control that dialogue, but at the same time,

396
00:51:34,230 --> 00:51:39,853
Is it a true listening meeting if we're going to control the dialogue?

397
00:51:39,893 --> 00:51:45,216
So I just, like I said, I think that this is a great idea.

398
00:51:45,276 --> 00:51:51,819
I think this is a process where we're bringing our body to the people and I think I've been

399
00:51:52,493 --> 00:51:59,239
you know, I've been negatively going at that with, especially with the zoning, but, um, I don't know.

400
00:51:59,259 --> 00:52:12,211
I just wanted us to consider that just a little bit more that, you know, having those meetings and, you know, wherever they may be, it could be at, at a, at a restaurant and just sitting with five or 10 neighbors and just listening.

401
00:52:12,331 --> 00:52:15,094
Cause we all know a lot of times when we hear.

402
00:52:15,854 --> 00:52:20,476
we have concerns in neighborhoods, we don't know until we get the phone call, right?

403
00:52:20,516 --> 00:52:35,164
So, and then we realize how that one concern doesn't just resonate in that one neighborhood, but throughout the community, and then we're now putting on our leadership hats to make some real substantive changes.

404
00:52:35,224 --> 00:52:44,509
So, you know, I just caution us not to really, I think just the innocence of it, of having,

405
00:52:45,743 --> 00:52:47,771
a listening session and going into the neighborhoods.

406
00:52:48,393 --> 00:52:50,099
Just think trying that alone.

407
00:52:51,082 --> 00:52:57,685
And when we get there, maybe share some topics that can get the topics that conversation started.

408
00:52:58,245 --> 00:53:07,389
But I think that if we're going to put limitations and talk about some of the things I've heard tonight from some of us that we're just going to turn people away, guys.

409
00:53:07,569 --> 00:53:11,630
They're just not going to really not going to resonate to what the intent was, I thought.

410
00:53:11,670 --> 00:53:14,612
So again, I appreciate the input.

411
00:53:14,632 --> 00:53:19,434
I just wanted to share my thoughts and what someone shared with me.

412
00:53:19,494 --> 00:53:20,414
So thank you.

413
00:53:22,564 --> 00:53:24,725
No, thank you, Councilor Scarpelli, appreciate that.

414
00:53:25,845 --> 00:53:26,385
Councilor Sang.

415
00:53:26,405 --> 00:53:31,846
Yeah, I think Councilor Scarpelli's points are well taken.

416
00:53:32,927 --> 00:53:47,030
In my experience at the neighborhood meetings or at the listening sessions, really like, I think people are really, feel really free to tell us whatever they want, even if it's really critical.

417
00:53:48,509 --> 00:53:53,497
And we certainly I've certainly heard that at meetings and I am sure other counselors who've done the.

418
00:53:54,309 --> 00:53:55,950
The meetings have heard that as well.

419
00:53:57,170 --> 00:54:06,075
It really is, I think, in practice a very open time for folks to just bring whatever is on their minds to us.

420
00:54:06,295 --> 00:54:17,960
And then they might have questions for us, and we can give our answers, at least speaking as individual counselors and not as on behalf of others.

421
00:54:19,359 --> 00:54:25,526
But in practice, it seems it's always been, to me, a very free-flowing place.

422
00:54:26,087 --> 00:54:30,533
And to the extent that there might be impressions of

423
00:54:37,725 --> 00:54:41,606
controlling discourse or anything, which has not been true to my experience.

424
00:54:42,466 --> 00:54:52,389
I think a lot of it is just making sure that residents have an equal chance to participate, to speak, and that they feel like they're free to speak as well.

425
00:54:52,469 --> 00:54:57,071
And like you noted, it's down to the facilitator to do that.

426
00:55:00,492 --> 00:55:02,372
Thank you.

427
00:55:03,453 --> 00:55:04,473
Counselor Lemon.

428
00:55:07,501 --> 00:55:27,246
Yeah, my colleagues' points are very well taken and I would like to clarify that the intent of these conversations is not to say that if residents come and they want to talk, we're going to try to silence them.

429
00:55:27,786 --> 00:55:29,847
That's not what's going on.

430
00:55:30,507 --> 00:55:34,628
The concern I had with the listening session, which I think

431
00:55:37,322 --> 00:55:54,734
was reflected in my colleagues and Councilor Callahan's remarks earlier was not that we were concerned, not so much that we were concerned that somebody was bringing their concerns to us because we can hear concerns all day, every day.

432
00:55:55,214 --> 00:56:04,342
The issue is when other residents that attended that same session come up later and say they feel like they didn't have the chance to speak.

433
00:56:04,662 --> 00:56:06,965
It was their first time going to that.

434
00:56:07,005 --> 00:56:14,771
It might have been their first time coming to an event with one of their city counselors.

435
00:56:15,232 --> 00:56:18,515
And they feel like they came there with their own set of concerns.

436
00:56:19,255 --> 00:56:23,277
and they didn't get to express it in that time period.

437
00:56:23,657 --> 00:56:28,498
And that is the situation that I personally would like to avoid.

438
00:56:28,618 --> 00:56:43,484
And I fully agree that just changing the format could be a solution where instead of having it be some overly moderated event, it could be a more informal setting in a restaurant as was suggested.

439
00:56:44,284 --> 00:57:06,501
It could feel like a much more friendly atmosphere that people come to something where it's set up to be listening and discussion rather than an event where people feel like the intent is to have too much moderation there.

440
00:57:07,162 --> 00:57:11,405
So that's the point that I wanted to make.

441
00:57:11,445 --> 00:57:12,786
Thank you very much.

442
00:57:14,451 --> 00:57:14,791
Thank you.

443
00:57:15,171 --> 00:57:15,772
Councilor Callahan.

444
00:57:18,253 --> 00:57:18,473
Thanks.

445
00:57:18,573 --> 00:57:19,753
I know we're pushing up on time.

446
00:57:19,773 --> 00:57:30,858
I was just hoping that we could look at wards 8 and 4 since those are the ones we're thinking of doing first and just brainstorm a few possible locations that we could reach out to and see if those might work.

447
00:57:32,599 --> 00:57:37,261
I think obviously in 8 is Colleen's which would not be a bad place.

448
00:57:37,361 --> 00:57:40,483
They've had plenty of, you know, city councilors up there.

449
00:57:41,244 --> 00:57:45,629
Their space I think that might be a good one also the Great American Beer Hall.

450
00:57:46,991 --> 00:57:53,619
So those be a couple for that space in for what we got in for this Goldilocks.

451
00:57:54,951 --> 00:57:56,012
I don't know them.

452
00:57:56,092 --> 00:58:01,576
I'm just trying to think of what are some... Oh, there's Tamper, right, is in four.

453
00:58:01,596 --> 00:58:04,298
Isn't Tamper in four?

454
00:58:04,318 --> 00:58:05,699
There's Danish Pastry in four.

455
00:58:05,719 --> 00:58:09,802
Danish Pastry, I think, is also... Because it's right there next to Tamper, so Danish Pastry and Tamper are both in four.

456
00:58:09,822 --> 00:58:13,325
I'm just trying to think of some options that we can reach out to.

457
00:58:14,225 --> 00:58:20,871
For eight, honestly, I would go with the Great American Beer Hall, just because that has pretty big tables in it.

458
00:58:20,992 --> 00:58:24,014
Colleen's is also, is Colleen's in four?

459
00:58:24,074 --> 00:58:30,901
I'd have to look, because some of these cutoffs, okay, or sorry, eight, I think it is, yeah.

460
00:58:32,402 --> 00:58:35,484
But yeah, I think they do have a lot of great options.

461
00:58:35,524 --> 00:58:46,092
My concerns with 4 is that there tend to be a lot of cafes along Boston Avenue, but some of them can be kind of small, so it depends on how many folks we want to get in there.

462
00:58:46,132 --> 00:58:51,076
I was also thinking about maybe Tufts has some space, but I'm not sure who to reach out to for that.

463
00:58:54,891 --> 00:58:55,231
Thank you.

464
00:58:55,991 --> 00:59:03,353
No, I think these are, I think it's a good suggestion to get started with boards eight and four and putting together some ideas and suggestions.

465
00:59:03,453 --> 00:59:14,937
And to anyone watching or listening, if they also have some thoughts and suggestions of some good places, you know, please feel free to email me and let me know.

466
00:59:14,997 --> 00:59:15,957
We can start putting that together.

467
00:59:17,098 --> 00:59:23,106
I know we are cutting close on time, but I do want to open up to any public comment in the room or on Zoom.

468
00:59:23,746 --> 00:59:25,208
Right now I have someone in the room.

469
00:59:36,170 --> 00:59:37,751
Patrick Clark in 14 Bennett Place.

470
00:59:38,532 --> 00:59:41,154
So three things that are really more logistical.

471
00:59:41,354 --> 00:59:45,076
I think it's a really good idea to start with a pilot program in four and eight.

472
00:59:45,237 --> 00:59:46,638
I think that's savvy.

473
00:59:47,798 --> 00:59:59,307
I think standardization is a good concept, but also keeping in mind it's like when you dig a hole in the ground and it's like, okay, there's rocks, there's soft clay, there's a pipe, there's a skeleton.

474
00:59:59,987 --> 01:00:10,133
when you look at Medford in these random, not random, but you look at the political boundaries of the different wards, you're going to get different pockets of different things in that cross section.

475
01:00:10,373 --> 01:00:22,600
So you're going to get pockets of frustration, you're going to get pockets of basically that are information deserts where people have no idea what's going on, you're going to get pockets of people who are already very tuned in and enthusiastic.

476
01:00:23,781 --> 01:00:27,363
So within those random cross sections, you're going to get

477
01:00:28,043 --> 01:00:35,212
A random cross section of that random cross section that actually shows up at the meeting and so I think keeping in mind that.

478
01:00:36,073 --> 01:00:40,939
From my experience, what I've seen is there's 3 general types of people that show up interest wise.

479
01:00:41,019 --> 01:00:42,762
There's people looking for a support group.

480
01:00:43,122 --> 01:00:46,887
There's people looking for a think tank and there's people looking for an action network.

481
01:00:47,427 --> 01:00:58,843
and the support group people are more inclined towards really wanting to build reconciliation and open a dialogue, and the think tank people are like policy wonk, like, okay, how do we do this?

482
01:00:58,903 --> 01:01:02,488
What can we think about and what can we implement?

483
01:01:03,167 --> 01:01:14,335
And then the action network people are thinking to themselves, like, I don't wanna be too woo-woo here, I don't wanna be too brainy here, I just wanna start moving and getting stuff done.

484
01:01:14,855 --> 01:01:26,343
So I think once you start interacting with people, getting a sense of how those people talk, and you don't just necessarily fall into one of those categories, you could be multiple, but I think talking to different people

485
01:01:27,756 --> 01:01:34,001
in the way that they seem to be inclined to want to engage will help reduce some of these animosities that emerge.

486
01:01:35,041 --> 01:01:49,912
The other thing is I think it will really help through that process, I think you can uncover some potential super volunteers in each of these wards that can really help extend your reach because to Councilor Lemming's point earlier, there's seven of you.

487
01:01:50,333 --> 01:01:53,175
Maybe in 2027 when there's 11, it will be more spread out.

488
01:01:53,915 --> 01:01:57,422
I think you need leverage within the wards and then the final thing is.

489
01:01:59,080 --> 01:02:10,789
Echoing my point from earlier, I think actually getting the word out about this stuff, some events that are already on the calendar, cleanup day is going to be May 2nd, and that's already open on the mayor's tab on the city website.

490
01:02:11,269 --> 01:02:23,178
If people host cleanup spots in the city in the different wards, that could be a good mechanism for actually meeting some of these people and getting word out to them, and maybe they could be some of those volunteers.

491
01:02:23,639 --> 01:02:27,001
Also, block parties in May, I don't know,

492
01:02:28,362 --> 01:02:38,906
if there's any rhythm to how people typically set up block parties, but there's kind of a month period between winter and summer where people are out and about, and maybe that can be leveraged too.

493
01:02:39,246 --> 01:02:40,006
So, thank you.

494
01:02:41,426 --> 01:02:42,227
Thank you very much.

495
01:02:44,127 --> 01:02:48,529
Any other public comments on Zoom?

496
01:02:53,911 --> 01:02:57,172
Okay, seeing none, it sounds like we

497
01:03:04,374 --> 01:03:04,554
Great.

498
01:03:04,614 --> 01:03:05,375
Thank you.

499
01:03:06,075 --> 01:03:13,661
It sounds like we've kind of started putting together a little bit of a plan and of a start working within wards eight and four.

500
01:03:13,861 --> 01:03:21,487
And you know also to Councillor Scarpelli's points as well you know we do we really want to make sure everyone feels

501
01:03:22,087 --> 01:03:34,581
Welcome, and voices are heard, so any thoughts, suggestions, again, please feel free to reach out to me, and I'm happy to collect them and add them in as we start kind of putting together more of a plan.

502
01:03:35,362 --> 01:03:40,528
So I think maybe we continue putting this together.

503
01:03:42,670 --> 01:03:47,592
identifying for wards eight and four and just confirming that we have the right spots for it.

504
01:03:48,272 --> 01:03:56,335
A little bit of a strategy in terms of the advertising plan for it and leaving it open enough for enough time for anyone to reach out.

505
01:03:57,076 --> 01:03:59,057
Love the idea of any super volunteers.

506
01:03:59,077 --> 01:04:07,680
So certainly in each of these different wards, if you would be willing to help, you know, please again reach out to me and we can start kind of putting that in there as well.

507
